column168: WE WERE UNLOADING TRAILER 92-0300 AT THE PORTLAND OR TERMINAL, WHEN WE NOTICED A BLACK PLASTIC JUG MARKED CORROSIVE, UPSIDE DOWN AND LEAKING. THE JUG WAS STACKED ON TOP OF OTHER FREIGHT AND HAD SHIFTED DURING THE TRIP FROM SALT LAKE CITY TO PORTLAND. WE REMOVED THE CONTAINER FROM THE TRAILER AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL USING QUICK DRY. THE FREIGHT BELOW THE JUG HAD CONTAMINATION ON THE SHRINK WRAP WHICH WE REMOVED AND REPLACED. THERE WAS NO INJURIES TO PERSONNEL OR TO OVERNITE PROPERTY. ALL CONTAMINATES WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER WITH NO HAZARD TO ENVIRONMENT.

column168: WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION, HE FOUND THAT ONE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING BLEACH HAD A HOLE IN THE SIDE APPROXIMATELY 6" FROM THE TOP.  ALL OF THE BLEACH ABOVE THAT LEVEL HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM AND ONTO THE BED OF THE TRAILER.  IT IS NOT POSSIBLE TO TELL AT WHAT POINT DURING THE TRIP THE HOLE WAS FORMED AND THE BLEACH STARTED TO LEAK OUT.  WE WILL CONTINUE OUR PRACTICE OF INSPECTING EVERY CONTAINER, TON, CYLINDER AND/OR DRUM FOR LEAKS OR DEFECTS PRIOR TO SHIPPING IT OUT.  THE RESIDUAL MATERIAL ON THE TRUCK WAS THOROUGHLY RINSED DOWN BY THE CUSTOMER AT HIS LOCATION.

column168: RAMP PERSONNEL WERE LOADING FEEDER PLANE WHEN THEY REALIZED THEY WERE GOING TO HAVE A BUMP SITUATION DUE TO BULK AND WEIGHT. THIS WAS WHEN I BECAME INVOLVED WITH SHIPMENT. I AM THE PERSON THAT DETERMINES WHAT FRT WILL BE BUMPED. THE REASON I CHOSE THIS SHIPMENT WAS BECAUSE OF WEIGHT AND PC COUNT. EIGHT PC WERE MOVED ON FEEDER, SEVEN WERE HELD. I NOTICED THERE WAS A GASOLINE SMELL COMING FROM ONE OF THE BOXES. THE BOX WAS OPENED UP AND IT HAD A GASOLINE CONTAINER INSIDE AS WELL AS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER, ALSO A CHAINSAW THAT APPARENTLY HAD GAS IN IT. GAS WAS LEAKING OUT INTO BOX. BOX WAS WET INSIDE. FRT WAS TAKEN TO OUR WAREHOUSE AND OUR WILMINGTON SORT HAZ MAT PEOPLE NOTIFIED.

ETC WOULD ALSO LIKE TO MAKE YOU AWARE THAT THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS ISSUED A SUMMONS FOR FAILING TO YIELD AT A STOP SIGN.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 5,600 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE INTO (2) TWO 4,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS WHICH WERE TIED TOGETHER BY A CONNECTING PIPE. column168: AT 9:30 A.M., AL BOITA ARRIVED AND STARTED DELIVERING PRODUCT TO MERRICKVILLE SERVICE STATION. THE GAS STATION OWNER, WHO WAS AT SITE WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED, NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES (DEC, FIRE DEPT, POLICE, FENLEY & NICKOL, FIRE MARSHALL & MOBIL MANAGEMENT). THE AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE. 213 TONS OF SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE GSX SECURE LANDFILL IN PINEWOOD, SOUTH CAROLINA. TOP SOIL WAS HAULED TO PUT THE AREA BACK IN SUITABLE CONDITION. A DRIVER MEETING WAS HELD TO REVIEW COMPANY POLICIES ON PARKING REGULATIONS. ALL DRIVERS WERE INFORMED THAT BECAUSE OF THE ABOVE MENTIONED SPILL, THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED. THE TANKER INVOLVED WAS TAKEN TO THE SHOP AND HANDLES WERE INSTALLED AT THE VALVE AREA IN ORDER FOR IT TO BE LOCKED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DURING TRACTOR/TRAILER DELIVERY AT STATION A CUSTOMER IN PRIVATE AUTOMOBILE DROVE ACROSS HOSE LEADING FROM TRAILER TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. IMPACT CAUSED FAILURE OF FITTINGS AT THE POINT WHERE THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK. DRIVER CLOSED TRAILER VALVE TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE. GASOLINE ON GROUND WAS DIKED AND REMOVED WITH ABSORBENT PADS. LOCAL FIRE DEPT SUPERVISED RESPONSE. INCIDENT REPORTED TO VT. AGENCY OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.

AFTER ARRIVING AT DESTINATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PLASTIC WRAP AROUND ONE PALLET HAD FAILED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO FALL. ROBERTSON WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL CLEANED SPILL. THE PART OF THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT WAS CONTAMINATED WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BLEACH AND THEN REPLACED.

column168: A DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PUT MORE PRODUCT IN AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) THAN TANK WOULD HOLD. OVERAGE SPILLED AROUND DISCHARGE FITTING AND SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. AT THE RECEIVER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE BAG HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. CLEAN UP WAS EFFECTED BY J R SIMPLOT RESPONSE TEAM USING BROOMS AND FINALLY A HIGH POWERED VACUUM. ALL OF THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS ACCEPTED BY THE RECEIVER.

column168: WE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM OUR CUSTOMER WHO SAID THERE WAS OIL ON THEIR BASEMENT FLOOR. WE SENT TO INVESTIGATE. HE FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF OIL ON BASEMENT FLOOR WHICH HE CLEANED UP. ALSO THE PACKAGE WAS NOT PACKED IN A CARDBOARD EXTERNAL PACK, WHICH IS AN INCORRECT SHIPPING PRACTICE (ISP ALSO WRITTEN). PROPER EXTERNAL PACK MAY HAVE PREVENTED ANY TYPE OF DAMAGE IN THE SMALL PARCEL ENVIRONMENT.

THIS PACKAGE WAS SENT TO WISCONSIN OVERGOODS DEPARTMENT AS OVERGOODS. IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER BY OAK CREEK NIGHT SORT. THE LABEL AND SHIPPER NUMBER WAS READABLE. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:50 A.M., FEBRUARY 10, 1990, TRAIN CREW ON TRAIN 1-403-19, WHILE MAKING A "SETOUT" AT HUTCHINSON, KS., NOTICED VAPORS COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 97865. THE ASSISTANT TRAINMASTER WAS NOTIFIED AND HE INSTRUCTED CREW TO SET CAR OUT TOWARD EAST END OF YARD AND ISOLATE CAR. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AT THE CAR AT 3:35 P.M. FEB. 20TH. UPON INSPECTION, THEY DISCOVERED THE GAGING DEVICE VALVE HANDLE HAD VIBRATED ABOUT 1/4 TURN OPEN. THIS VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND ALSO THE PACKING NUT WAS LOOSE ON GAGING ROD AND WAS TIGHTENED. THIS CORRECTED THE PROBLEM AND WAS COMPLEDTED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 P.M. FEB. 20TH. AS INFORMATION NONE OF THE PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND AS IT VAPORIZED
NOT SURE WHETHER PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED IN TRANSIT OR BROKEN DURING THE SORT AT THE STATION. CONTACTED DANGEROUS GOODS IN MEMPHIS. WE PROPERLY CLEANED UP THE SPILL. CONTENTS IN DG DRUM.

column168: AFTER FUELING AT OZARA, MO, DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK UNDER 3 OF 8 FLOW BINS ON BOARD. THE SHIPPER, MOBIL OIL IN JOLIET, IL., WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SITE. HATCH DOORS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BINS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE BINS WRAPPED IN PLASTIC. THERE BINS WERE LOADED INSIDE AT MOBIL OIL IN JOLIET, IL. THEY WERE THEN MOVED OUTSIDE TO COOL WITH NO LIDS ON THE TOPS. DURING THE STORAGE PERIOD WHICH LASTED SEVERAL DAYS, IT SNOWED. WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED SOUTH INTO A WARMER CLIMATE, THE SNOW MELTED CAUSING WATER TO MOVE DOWN THROUGH THE CATALYST AND DROP THROUGH THE HATCH DOORS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BINS. AFTER THE LOAD WAS REWORKED, IT PROCEEDED SOUTH TO BRAITHWAITE, LA. 2-12-90, DRIVER CALLED FROM AMITE, LA, AND REPORTED SAME 3 FLOW BINS WERE LEAKING AGAIN. MOBIL OIL WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT IN A RESPONSE CREW. FLOW BINS WERE REPACKED, TRAILER DECK CLEANED AND LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF TWENTY 5 GALLON PAILES, 12 WERE SITTING ONTOP OF A PALLET THESE WERE UNLOAD FIRST WITH OUT PROBLEM.  THE REMAINING 8 WERE IN BETWEEN TWO PALLETS THESE WERE STACKED TWO HIGH. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE BETWEEN THEPAILS AND THE PALLETS AND DURING TRANSIT ONE OF THE BOTTOM PAILS BOUNCED ONTO IT'S SIDE AND WAS CRUSHED BY THE WEIGHT OF THE PAIL ON TOP.  THIS CAUSED THE LID TO OPEN AND CONTENT TO SPILL IN TRAILER. TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE FROM THE PAIL OR ANY LEAKAGE FROM THE TRAILER THE PAIL WAS ISOLATED AND REMOVED.  TO CONFINE THE SPILL BRIAN LIM W/ SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND SAID TO SPREAD SPEED DRY MISTURE OVER MATERIAL. MATERIAL WAS LLOWED TO DRY AND SWEPT UP FOR CONSOLIDATION ONTO CARBOARD FOR LATTER DUMPING.  PER BRIAN LIM W/SHIPPER MATERIAL WAS ALLOWED TO DRY FOR 3 TO 4 DAYS THEN WAS DISPOSED OF AS NORMAL SOLID WASTE.  TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR DRY OUT IN THE YARD.  TO PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF REACURANCE PAILS SHOULD HAVE ONLY BEEN STACKED ON THE FLOOR AND DUNNAGE USED TO BRACE THE SHIPMENT TO HELP MINIMIZE MOVEMENT.  ADDITIONALLY, PAILS SHOULD NO HAVE BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF PALLET.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: A RELEASE OF A WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID OCCURRED AT THE PHOENIX STORAGE FACILITY ON FEBRUARY 2, 1990 AT 10:30 AM.  APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS OF MIXED SOLVENT WASTE SPILLED FROM A DRUM DURING A ROUTINE DRUM MOVEMENT.  THE DRUM SLIPPED FROM THE DRUM GRABBERS ON THE FORKLIFT WHILE THE DRUM WAS BEING LIFTED TO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK (APPROXIMATELY 4FT).  THE BOTTOM CHIME RUPTURED FORM THE FORCE OF THE FALL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES ASSOCIATEED WITH THIS RELEASE.  THIS WAS NOT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY RELEASE.  CWMI PERSONNEL ACTED QUICKLY TO INVERT THE DRUM AND STOP THE RELEASE. THE FACILITY EMERGENCY COORDINATOR CHECKED THE EXTENT OF THE RELEASE AND DETERMINED THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATELY THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH  OR THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE FACILITY WAS NOT EVACUATED.  CONTAMINATED GRAVEL AND SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND CONTAINERIZED FROM A 30 SQ. FT. AREA TO A DEPTH OF BETWEEN 1/2 AND 2 INCHES. FOUR DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS GENERATED.  THE CONTAINERS WERE STORED ONSITE PENDING APPROVAL FOR OFF-SITE SHIPMENT.  CONTAMINATED SOIL PROFILE IS K06386.  10 SOIL SAMPLETS WERE TAKEN FROMTHE CLEANED AREA AND SUBMITTED TO AN OUSIDE LAB FOR VERIFICATION OF CLEANUP.  SAMPLES WERE ALSO TAKEN FROM THE FIELD BEHIND THE PROBERTY TO DETERMINE BACKGROUND LEVELS.  ADDITIONAL ACTION WILL BE TAKEN AFTER RESULTS OF THE SAMPLE ANALYSIS ARE OBTAINED.  ALL APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL WILL BE GIVEN ADDITIONAL TRAINING INDRUM HANDLING AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE TO LEAKING CONTAINER.

column168: ABF DOCK WORKER WAS OPERATING A FORKLIFT INTHE CONTAINER IN WHICH THE 12 DRUMS WERE IN.  THERE WERE 6 DRUMS ON 1 PALET LOADE ON TOP OF ANOTHER PALLET WITH THE OTHER 6 DRUMS.  WHEN FORKLIFT OPERATOR TRIED TO PICK UP THE TOP PALLET THAT WAS DOUBLE STACKED ON EACH OTHER, IT CAUSED 1 DRUM TO FALL OFF THE BOTTOM PALLET AND TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTENTS OF THEFALLEN DRUM SPILLED TO THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AND THROUGH THE WOOD DECKING OF THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE GROUND BELOW.  WE COULD NOT TELL HOW MUCH OF THE LIQUID SPILLED OUT AT THE TIME.  THE ORIGIN TERMINAL FROM OAKLAND WHO WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LOADING OF THIS CONTIANER. WILL BE ADVISED OF THIS HAZARDOUS INCIDENTS TO AVOID FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS SAME KIND.

THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS THAT THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED WHICH CAUSED HIM TO OVER-FILL CUSTOMER'S TANK.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL #2 DISCHARGED ON THE GROUND.  THIS WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED ON LAND.  THERE WAS NO DANGER TO STREAMS, SANITARY SEWERS OR STORM DRAINS.  THE CUSTOMER'S CONTAMINATED TOPSOIL WAS REPLACED AND THE GRASS RE-SEEDED.  THE DRIVER WAS SEVERLY REPRIMANDED FOR HIS NEGLIGENCE.

column168: DRIVER/DOCKMAN FELT THEY INHALED FUMES FROM A BOX OF CORROSIVE. AFTER CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINERS, THERE IS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE, BUT SOME RESIDUE ON THE BOTTLES. DOCKMEN WERE TAKEN OUT OF THE AREA, WHERE THEY COMPLAINED OF WATERY EYES, HEADACHES, AND SORE THROAT. THEY WERE SENT /TAKEN TO THE DOCTOR, WHERE HE FOUND NOTHING WRONG WITH THEM. I FELT THE APPROPRIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN WHEN THE WORKERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND THE AREA INVESTIGATED. THE BOTTLES DID HAVE RESIDUE ON THEM. THEY WERE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE AS THEY CAME IN. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE TO CLEAN UP OR DISPOSE OF.
WHILE AIR UNLOADING CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED AND PRODUCT DISCHARGED OUT OF OVERFLOW PIPE. PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. PRODUCT WAS ALSO PUT INTO THEIR PIT TO BE DISPOSED OF.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR UNLOADING AT DESTINATION.  HE PROCEEDE TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  DURING THE PROCESS HE HEARD LIQUID RUNNING AND WHEN INVESTIGATING HE FOUND MATERIAL FUNNING FROM THE OVER FLOW VENT ON THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  HE SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY AND NOTIFIED THE RECEIVER.  THE RECEIVER CONFIRMED THAT HIS TANK WAS FULL AND TOLD OUR DRIVER TO RETURN THE REMAINING MATERIAL TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: DELTA AIR LINES, INC. ACTS AS THE GROUND HANDLING AGENT FOR COMAIR AT THE FORT LAUDERDALE/HOLLYWOOD INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT LOCATED IN FORT LAUDERDALE, FL.  THESE SHIPMENTS WERE TENDERED TO OUR SMALL PACKAGE ACCEPTANCE FACILITY AND THE CONTENTS WERE DESCRIBED TO US AS LIQUID DETERGENT-INDUSTRIAL.  THE TWO PIECES WERE LOADED ON THE COMAIR AIRCRAFT AND DURING TAXI OUT FROM THE TERMINAL THE COCKPIT CREW BECAME AWARE OF A STRONG ODOR.  NOT KNOWING THE ORIGIN OF THIS ODOR THEY ELECTED TO RETURN TO THE GATE AND INVESTIGATE.  THE CARGO BECAME SUSPECT AND UPON EXAMINATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE SHIPMENTS WERE IMPROPERLY DESCRIBED BY THE SHPPER.  BOTH SHIPMENTS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND A REPORT WAS MADE TO THE LOCAL FAA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICE AS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.

column168: THE DESCRIBED CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED AT THE BACK OF A SEMI TRUCK TRAILER THAT WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE DENVER RAMP FACILITY.  TWO SIDES OF THE BOXES WERE SATURATED AND BROKEN OPEN. EIGHT PLASTIC CONTAINERS CONTAINING APPROX 3 OZ EACH OF LIQUID WERE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK.  AFTER BEING INFORMED OF THIS SPILL I INSTRUCTED THE OTHER EMPLOYEES TO OT GO NEAR OR TOUCH THE UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO OBTAIN A METAL DRUM AND GLOVES TO REMOVE THE BOX AND PLASTIC CONTAINERS FROM THE AREA.  AFTER SECURING THE SPILL I NOTIFIED OUR HAZ GOODS DEPT. IN MEMPHIS FOR NOTIFICAITON AND PROPER SHIPPING PROCEDURE.  I ALSO CONTACTED THE SENDER AND RECIPIENT TO OBTAIN WHATEVER KNOWLEDGE THEY HAD ON THE UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE.  THE SENDER WAS A FEC STATION OUT OF OMAHA/NB.  THEY HAD ATTACHED A NEW AIRBILL TO THE PACKAGE AS THE ORIGINAL HAD FALLEN OFF. I THEN CONTACTED THE RECIPIENT WHO TURNED OUT TO BE THE ORIGINAL SENDER.  I WAS FIRST TOLD THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS HUMAN TISSUE AND COULD BE A CONTAMINATE.  AFTER FURTHER RESEARCH, I WAS THEN TOLD THAT THE HUMAN TISSUE WAS NOT CONTAMINATED, BUT THAT THE LIQUID SUBSTANCE SURROUNDING THE TISSUE WOULD BE DANGEROUS IF IT CAME IN CONTACT WITH SKIN, EYES, ETC.  I THEN INSTRUCTED ALL EMPLOYEES WORKING THE TRUCK TO WASH THEIR FACE AND HANDS AS A PRECAUTIONAY MEASURE.  THE BOX HAD MARKINGS OF THE FOLLOWING: ORM-E.  THIS BOX SHOULD HAVE HAD A CLASS 9 STICKER AND HAZ PAPERWORK WITH IT.  IT IS POSSIBLE THESE FELL OFF DURING SHIPPING, BUT I DO QUESTION THE INITIAL PAPERWORK ON THE PACKAGE.  IF THE PROPER LABELS HAD BEEN AFFIXED, IT WOULD HAVE ALERTED THE OMA STATION TO QUESTION IF THEY SHOULD HAVE SENT IT THROUGH THE SYSTEM.  THE AREAS IN THE TRUCK WAS SPRAYED WITH BLEACH AND HOSED DOWN AS THE LAST CLEANUP MEASURE.

IT WAS OVERPACKED AND CONTAINED. THE DISPOSAL WAS HANDLED BY ICI AND I.T. CORPORATION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED MUCH DIFFICULTY IN RAISING THE BOX ONTO THE FRAME AND IN DOING SO THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE BOX CAUSING THE LID TO BUCKLE SLIGHTLY.  IN DROPPING THE BOX AT GSX PINEWOOD FACILITY THE LOAD SHIFTED AGAIN, BUCKLING THE LID AND ALLOWED APPROX 30 TO 40 GALLONS OF WASTE TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF BY GSX PERSONNEL WORKING AT THE FACILITY AND THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS DISPOSED OF AS ORIGINALLY SCHEDULED.  THE SPILL OCCURRED IN A DESIGNATED CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS NEVER A THREAT TO THE PUBLIC OR ANY OF THE WORKERS AT THE FACILITY.

WHEN HE TIPPED DRUM TO INVERT, (SO LEAK WOULD BE UPPERMOST) MORE CONTENTS SPILLED OUT. ONCE DRUM WAS INVERTED, THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE DRIVER CONCENTRATED ON CONTAINING THE RELEASED PRODUCT BY DIKING WITH ABSORBENT PILLOWS TAKEN FROM THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE KIT CARRIED IN THE VW&R TRUCK. ONCE NOTIFIED BY THE DRIVER, VW&R EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED AND CLEAN-UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHIN THE 1/2 HOUR. ONCE THE AREA WAS CLEAN, THE OWNER OF THE PROPERTY (CUSTOMER) WAS NOTIFIED, AND HE INSPECTED THE AREA.  THE CLEAN-UP MET HIS SATISFACTION, AND THE DAMAGED DRUM, NOW IN A RECOVERY DRUM, AND THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE BRANCH FOR NEUTRALIZATION AND DISPOSAL.

I WAS ABOUT HALF WAY ACROSS BRIDGE WHEN A FORD PICK-UP CAME AROUND THE CORNER IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD. I TURNED TO THE OUTSIDE TO GIVE HIM AS MUCH ROOM AS POSSIBLE. WHEN I TRIED TO CONTINUE TO TURN TO THE LEFT, THE TIRES WOULD NOT RESPOND. I HAD TAKEN MY FOOT OFF THE PEDAL AND I TRIED APPLYING BREAKING POWER BY PULLING DOWN ON THE HAD BAR, THERE STILL WAS NO RESPONSE. THE TRUCK STARTED OVER THE EDGE. I TRIED TO STEER DOWN THE EMBANKMENT. THE NEXT THING I REMEMBER IS THE WATER HITTING MY FACE--THE TRUCK SLID ALONG THE BOTTOM AND STOPPED. I RAISED MY HEAD OUT OF THE WATER. TRIED TO CATCH MY BREATH AND REALIZED I WAS PINNED BETWEEN STEERING WHELL AND SEAT. MY LEG WAS STUCK UNDER THE DASH. THERE WAS BLOOD ON MY SHIRT. SOME ONE ON TOP CAME TO HELP ME. I LOOKED AT THE TANKER FROM THE TOP OF THE ROAD AND NOTICED IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE RUPTURE DISC.

column168: WHILE PPG DRIVER WAS ENTERING INTERSECTION, THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #2 RAN A STOP SIGN CAUSING OUR DRIVER TO TAKE EVASIVE ACTION TO AVOID A COLLISION. A CHECK OF THE TRAILER REVEALED THAT THE TOTE TANKS IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER BECAME INSECURE AND SLID FORWARD, CRUSHING THE DRUMS.  PPG DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SAFETY OFFICE IN DELAWARE, OHIO.  THEY THEN CONTACTED THE O.H. MATERIALS TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP. TO IMPROVE SECURITY, THE LOAD PATTERN IS BEING CHANGED FROM USING ONE LOAD BAR TO TWO.

CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS AND WAS PLACED TO AN ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS. CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. CAR WAS LEAKING FROM DOME DUE TO BAD DOME CASKET.  REPRESENTATIVE FROM SIMPSON PAPER INSPECTED CAR AND REPLACED DOME GASKET AND CAR WAS OKAY TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WE WERE PUMPING GASOLINE OUT OF THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO OUR CARGO TANK WHEN THE CARGO TANK OVERFILLED WITH GASOLINE AND A 15 GALLON SPILL OCCURED. THE SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED THROUGH BETTER COMMUNICATION BETWEEN THOSE INVOLVED IN THE ACTIVITY.  NEW MC306 TRAILERS BEING PURCHASED IN THE FUTURE WILL BE EQUIPPED WITH MECHANICAL DEVICES TO PREVENT SIMILAR OCCURRENCES.

SHORTLY AFTER THE PRODUCT FLOWED INTO CUSTOMER'S TANK, DRIVER NOTICED LEAK WHERE A 3" FITTING WAS SCREWED ONTO THE CARGO TANK UNLOADING PIPE. AIR PRESSURE WAS REMOVED FROM TANK AND ALL VALVES CLOSED. DRIVER DISCONNECTED TRANSFER HOSE AND INSTALLED  A DIFFERENT 3" FITTING. SAME LEAK OCCURED. A 3RD FITTING WAS TRIED WITH SAME RESULTS. UNLOADING ATTEMPTS WERE TERMINATED. SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET AND WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing

WE PUT OIL DRY ON IT AND PUT IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM WAITING FOR DISPOSITION THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS INSTRUCTED.

A BULLET ENTERED THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER APPROX 2 FEET TO THE REAR OF THE PLACARD. THE BULLET TRAVELLED THRU A 1 GALLON CONTAINER OF PARAQUAT AND ENTERED A SECOND CONTAINER. 2 GALLONS LEAKED. OH MATERIALS FROM ATLANTA, GA HANDLED CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION. TRAILER FLOOR WAS REPLACED.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: DURING UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE'S DOCK OUR DRIVER PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON DRUM CAUSING A SMAL PINHOLE LEAK. COLORADO SPRINGS HAZ MAT TEAM RESPONDED. THEY PUT THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER, CLEANED UP ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT. MOTOR CARGO HAS RETURNED THE SALVAGED DRUM TO SHIPPER.

OUR TRUCK WAS DRIVING WEST ON LYNDON AVE IN DETROIT TO MAKE A DELIVERY AT 8139 LYNDON. ON ARRIVAL THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER CALLED THE PLANT MANAGER.  THE PLANT MANAGER WENT TO THE SCENE AND INVESITGATED.  THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A MANWAY WORKING LOOSE FROM A PORTABLE TANK. THE STOPPING, STARTING AND TURNING RESULTED IN APPROX 5 -7 GALLONS SLOSHING OUT OF THE TOTE AND ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THIS RESULTED IN APPROX 3-5 GALLONS BEING RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN ROUTE FROM TEXAS CITY, TX TO NEW ORLEANS, LA, LOADED. HE STOPPED AT THE PERKINS RD. EXIT AND I-10 IN BATON ROUGE, LA, TO CHECK HIS TIRES.  AS HE WAS WALKING AROUND THE UNIT HE OBSERVED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE #1 COMPARTMENT AT THE BELLY VALVE FLANGE. HE TOOK UNIT TO PORT ALLEN TERMINAL. OUR MECHANIC TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE VALVE FLANGE, BUT THE DRIP CONTINUED. UNION CARBIDE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED AT THE PORT ALLEN TERMINAL UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF UNION CARBIDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM UNION CARBIDE AT TAFT, LA.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO TRAILER 4529, AND WAS DELIVERED ON MONDAY 2-26-90 TO MAGNOLIA CHEMICAL CO. IN NEW ORLEANS, WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: THE SHIPPER, ROHM AND HAAS CO. LOADED TH 68 METAL DRUMS ON A STEAMSHIP CONTAINER ON FEB 20, 1990 AT THEIR PLANT IN PHILA PA CARRIER, ENGLE OOSTDYK, INC. TRANSPORTED THE CONTAINER FROM PHIA, PA TO ELMOOD PARK, NJ FOPR SUBSEQUENT EXPORT DELIVERY TO PORT NEARK, NJ.  AT ELMWOOD PARK TERMINAL A SLIGHT LEAK EMANATING FROM THE TRAILER WAS NOTICED BY A DRIVER. A REPORT WAS MADE IMMEDIATELY TO CHEMTREC AS WELL AS SHIPPER. SHIPPER SENT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO HANDLE SITUATION. THEY FOUND THE ONE DAMAGED DRUM, PLACED IT IN RECOVERY DRUM, AND TOOK IT BACK TO THEIR PLANT AFTER UNLOADING ALL DRUMS, PERFORMED STANDARD CLEAN-UP OF ALL SPILLAGE, AND RELOADED THE SHIPPMENT ON ANOTHER CONTAINER.
FORKS ON TOW MOTOR PUNCTURED A HOLE IN DRUM. DRUM WAS SET UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT SPILLAGE AND PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

DUE TO FREIGHT SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, THE FIBER DRUM TOPPLED OVER AND DRUM TOP CAME LOOSE ALLOWING SOME POWDER TO SIFT OUT OF THE DRUM. WHEN THE TRAILER ARRIVED AT OUR BROOKLYN NY TERMINAL, CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED (INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGY OF AVENEL, NJ). THEY VACUUMED THE SPILLED POWDER AND PLACED FIBER DRUM IN A STEEL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DRUM. STEEL DRUM WAS PICKED UP AT OUR BROOKLYN NY TERMINAL BY REPRESENTATIVES OF THE SHIPPER.  THE DOCK FOREMAN IN CHARGE OF THE TRAILER LOADING CREW AT OUR BALTIMORE TERMINAL WAS GIVEN THREE DAYS OFF WITHOUT PAY.

column168: VEHICLE PARKED AT A REST AREA. DURING VEHICLE INSPECTION DRIVER NOTICED A PUDDLE OF LIQUID UNDER THE TANK TRAILERS. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED CHEMTREC, DISPATCH, AND THE PENNA STATE POLICE. UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THE REST AREA WAS SHUT DOWN. THE NEW YORK STATE POLICE RESPONDED THAT A SPILL OF 2-3 GALLONS WAS FOUND AT THE NY-PA TOLL BOOTH AREA. AN EMERGENCY REPONSE CONTRACTOR, OH MATERIALS OF PITTSBURG, WAS DISPATCHED TO EFFECT A CLEAN-UP OF THE REST AREA AND TOLL BOOTH AREA. A TANK TRAILER WAS BROUGHT IN BY CHEMICAL LEAMAN TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED UNIT.  THE SECOND TRAILER WAS NOT REGISTERED FOR WASTE HOWEVER, WE DID GET PERMISSION FROM PA OFFICIALS TO DO THE TRANSLOADING. THE SECOND TRAILER WAS TO ACT ONLY AS A TEMPORARY STORAGE CONTAINER. DURING THE TRANSLOADING PROCESS AN ADDITIONAL 3 GALLONS SPILLED. AT THAT POINT A DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTACT THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.

OUR TRAILER LOADED AT ROHM AND HAAS, DEER PARK, TX.  THE UNIT WAS BROUGHT TO OUR YARD TO BE DELIVERED THE NEXT DAY. AN EMPLOYEE SMELLED AN ODOR AND INVESTIGATED. HE FOUND A SMALL LEAK AND THEN PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND CALLED THE PROPER PEOPLE. THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT EFFINGHAM, IL TO FUEL AND NOTICED A LEAK UNDER 2 OF 8 FLOW BINS HE WAS TRANSPORTING. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE. THESE BINS WERE LOADED INSIDE AT MOBIL OIL IN JOLIET. THEY WERE THEN MOVED OUTSIDE TO COOL WITH NO LIDS ON THEM.  DURING THE STORAGE PERIOD WHICH LASTED SEVERAL DAYS, IT SNOWED.  WHILE IN TRANSIT THE SNOW BEGAN TO MELT ALLOWING WATER TO MOVE DOWN THROUGH THE CATALYST AND DROP THROUGH THE HATCH DOORS ON HTE BOTTOM OF THE BINS.  THE RESPONSE TEAM SECURED THE DOORS AND THE LOAD WAS RETURNED TO MOBIL OIL AT JOLIET. NOTHING WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.

PRINCIPAL CAUSE OF DISCHARGE WAS THE CONDITION OF THE BANDIT CLAMP SECURING THE LOADING HOSE TO THE LEASE AUTOMATIC CUSTODY TRANSFER METER UNIT. FLOW RATE WAS 6 .82 BARRELS PER MINUTE. PRESSURE LOOSENED THE CLAMP AND THREW THE HOSE. MOST OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY A DIKED WALL SURROUNDING THE LACT UNIT. PROPERTY DAMAGE CONSISTED OF SOIL STAINS. ABSORBENT PADS USED TO MOP UP POOLED OIL WHICH GATHERED AT GROUNDWATER PUDDLES. OPERATOR DISCOVERED DISCHARGE IMMEDIATELY AND CLOSED VALVES ON BOTH SIDES OF THE DISCHARGE.  MAINTENANCE TECHNICIAN HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER INSTALLATION OF HOSE BANDITS; OPERATORS WERE REMINDED TO CONDUCT FREQUENT EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS.

THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ON PALLETS, AND THE RUPTURE IN THE DRUM WAS LOCATED NEAR THE BOTTOM. IT MOST LIKELY WAS CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.THE HARDENED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED OUT BY A TRAILER REPAIR FACILITY IN MADISON, WI.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO MAINTAIN VEHICLE IN ONE LANE. AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE VEHICLE BACK ON TO THE HIGHWAY, IT TURNED ON ITS SIDE. DAMAGE TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS CAUSED BY OTHER FREIGHT AS VEHICLE TURNED ON ITS SIDE.  RESPONDING TO THE INCIDENT WERE:  SMALLEY TRANSPORTATION CO. REPRESENTATIVES, MARTIN COUNTY'S EMERGENCY REPONSE UNIT, FL HIGHWAY PATROL, DOT OFFICIALS, AND STEVE'S TOWING OF LAKE WORTH, FL.  THE UNIT WAS TOWED TO THE YARD OF STEVE'S TOWING SHERE IT REMAINED FOR 12 DAYS. THEN IT WAS TOWED TO SMALLEY TRANSPORTATION CO.'S WEST PALM BEACH TERMINAL.
OUR DRIVER NOTICED AN ODOR. HE FOUND A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE CAP ON THE LIQUID LINE. HE REMOVED THE CAP DRAINING THE PRODUCT INTO A BUCKET. HE REPLACED THE GASKET IN THE CAP.

THE NUMBER 4 CARBON MONOXIDE TUBE SAFETY FAILED ALLOWING THE CONTENTS OF THE TUBE TO ESCAPE AND FLARE OFF.  AN INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT REVEALED THAT A MECHANIC FAILED TO INSTALL THE PROPER SAFETY IN THE TUBE. THE MECHANIC INSTALLED THE FUSE METAL PORTION OF THE SAFETY, BUT FAILED TO INSTALL THE SHEAR WASHER, DISC AND SAFETY WASHER.  A RETRAINING PROGRAM WAS HELD IMMEDIATELY TO ENSURE EACH MECHANIC WAS FULLY AWARE OF THE INCIDENT AND HANDS ON TRAINING WAS ADMINISTERED INDIVIDUALLY TO EACH MECHANIC.

ON FEBRUARY 24, 1990 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 P.M., THE DRIVER, MR. WARNER RICH, NOTICED SEVERAL FLOW BINS ON HIS TRAILER WERE GETTING HOT. MR. RICH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER FOR INSTRUCTIONS. EMTECH AND ENNIS, TX FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE BINS WERE PURGED WITH WATER AND NITROGEN TO COOL. THE SHIPPER AND PACKAGING COMPANIES ARRIVED TO PACK THE BINS WITH DRY ICE AND RESEALED EACH BIN. SEVEN BINS ON TWO TRAILERS WERE INVOLVED. FIVE PEOPLE (WARNER & RAMONA RICH, RAY MESSER, EDWINA PITTMAN AND RHONDA ATWOOD) WERE TREATED AND RELEASED AS A CAUTION FOR EXPOSURE TO THE FUMES FROM THE FLOW BINS. WE WILL FOLLOW-UP WITH THE SHIPPER, PACKAGING COMPANY AND THE ENNIS, TX FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION AND FOLLOW-UP REPORT. PLEASE FINE ATTACHED COPIES OF THE INCIDENT REPORTS FROM THE RESPONDING FIRE DEPARTMENTS AND THE SHIPPING PAPERS ISSUED BY STAR ENTERPRISES. THE MEDICAL RECORDS OF THOSE RECEIVING MEDICAL ASSISTANCE. AFTER DONNING PROTECTIVE CARTRIDGE MASKS, MYSELF AND FRAN VANCE, PART-TIME HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST, AIRBORNE EXPRESS, WILMINGTON, OHIO APPROACHED THE SLIDE WHERE THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED. INITIAL INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT A FIBREBOARD BOX WAS LEAKING A WHITE COLORED LIQUID. AFTER OPENING PACKAGE THE NEXT INNER RECEPTACLE WAS FOUND TO BE ANOTHER FIBREBOARD BOX. UPON OPENING THIS BOX THE INNERMOST CONTAINERS WERE ONE GLASS BABY FOOD JAR AND ONE PLASTIC VASELINE JAR. THE WHITE SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM THE VASELINE JAR. THE CUSHIONING/ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS A PAPER-TYPE CLOTH. DUE TO THE ODOR OF THIS SHIPMENT TWO PEOPLE WORKING NEAR THE AREA BECAME NAUSEOUS AND COMPLAINED OF A HEADACHE. THE MSDS STATED THAT THIS SHIPMENT WAS PAINT. UNDER 49 CFR PAINT IS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN 1263. THIS SHIPMENT IS CONSIDERED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND IS BEING HELD IN THE WILMINGTON HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS SHIPMENT HAD OLD MARKINGS STATING DRY ICE ORM-A UN 1845 THAT HAD NOT BEEN REMOVED OR OBLITERATED. ON 2-15-90 AT APPROXIMATELY 0140 HRS. A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS, WILMINGTON, OHIO. THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED ON A SLIDE IN THE SORT CENTER. UPON APPROACHING THE SLIDE, INITIAL INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT A FIBREBOARD BOX WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID. UPON OPENING THE FIBREBOARD BOX IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN AN ORANGE BIOHAZARD BAG WITH THE BIOHAZARD SYMBOL AND MARKINGS. THE BIOHAZARD BAG WAS SECURED AT THE TOP BUT WAS LEAKING THE CLEAR LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG. ALSO USED FOR THE SHIPMENT WAS STYROFOAM PEANUTS. DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR OF THE LIQUID, THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE WILMINGTON HAZ MAT SORT UNTIL A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) COULD BE OBTAINED. THE MSDS STATED THAT THE LIQUID WAS FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION. UNDER 49 CFR FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION IS CONSIDERED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLASSIFIED AS AN ORM-A. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HEL UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE WILMINGTON HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: UPON INVESTIGATION OF THIS SHPT, DON FLOREA (HAZ MAT SPECIALIST) FOUND THE INNER METAL CAN TO BE DENTED ON THE SIDE. THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE TOP CLOSURE ONLY. THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT USED IN THE PACKAGE. THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS WET ON THE LOWER CORNER. THE SHPT WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR WHICH WAS CONTAINED BY DOUBLE BAGGING IT AND REPACKING IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM (DOT APPROVED). AFTER RELEASE BY THE FAA , THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER. SHPT WAS HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PRIOR TO FAA INVESTIGATION .

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: HERITAGE TRANSPORT DRIVER, RANDY THOMPSON, WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF SUPPLEMENTAL FUEL FROM HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INDPLS. TO LONESTAR INDUSTRIES, GREENCASTLE, IN. MR. THOMPSON WAS APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION OF US 40 & SR 39, THE LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION TURNED YELLOW, HE STOPPED THE TRUCK ABRUPTLY CAUSING MOVEMENT OF LIQUID WITHIN THE TANKER. THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE LIQUID CAUSED A WASHOUT LID TO POP OPEN RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 35 GALS OF SUPPLEMENTAL FUEL ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES WHO DISPATCHED FIRE FIGHTERS FROM SEVERAL LOCAL AGENCIES AND A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OFFICER FROM INDIANA STATE POLICE. HERITAGE ACTIVATED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (HR/E) WHO IN TURN CLEANED THE SPILL RESIDUE FROM THE SPILL SITE AND DRUMMED THE RESIDUAL FOR ALTERNATE DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH RCRA REGULATION. JIM ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED AT NRC AND ASSIGNED 8760 AS THE INCIDENT NUMBER. POST ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THE PRIMARY CAUSE WAS FAULTY DESIGN IN LID CLOSURE DEVICE. IT HAS BEEN CORRECTED AND SAFETY SEALS WILL BE USED AS A SECONDARY SECUREMENT MEASURE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DESCRIPTION OF INCIDENT:  OUR DRIVER WAS HEADED E/B ON THE L.I.E. AND PASSING ENTRANCE RAMP TO L.I.E. FROM RT 110 WHEN HE WAS STRUCK BY A VEHICLE ATTEMPTING TO ENTER ROADWAY. THE DISCHARGE AREA WAS STRUCK SHEARING OFF THE COUPLINGS ON COMPARTMENTS #1 & 2. APPROX 40 GALS WERE LOST IMMEDIATELY. #1 INTERNAL CONTINUED TO SEEP DUE TO THE IMPACT CAUSING IT TO TORQUE AND NOT SEAT PROPERLY. AN ADDITIONAL 72 GALLONS WERE LOST UNTIL WE WERE ABLE TO SECURE DISCHARGE LINE WITH A 4" EXPANDER PIPE PLUG. ACTION TAKEN:  OUR DRIVER, E. RADA, AFTER BEING STRUCK, PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND CALLED FOR HELP ON HIS C.B. RADIO. A PASSING TRUCK RECIEVED THE MESSAGE AND PROCEEDED TO THE NEXT EXIT TO CALL POLICE. ED GOT OUT OF THE VEHICLE TO SEE HOW THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER CAR WAS AND TO ASSESS THE DAMAGE. HE DETERMINED THAT HE STILL HAD A LEAK IN THE #1 INTERNAL. ED STUFFED RAGS AND THE TRAFFIC CONE INTO THE DISCHARGE LINE IN ORDER TO SLOW THE SEEPAGE UNTIL HELP COULD ARRIVE. AT APPROX. 00:15 M.A. D'ANTONIO WAS NOTIFIED BY SUFFOLK CTY. POLICE THAT A SHELL TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT AND THAT HE NEEDED TO COME TO THE SCENE. MARIO ARRIVED AROUND 00:35 AND IMMEDIATELY MET WITH THE FIRE DEPT. AND POLICE TO ASSIST. AFTER AN ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK BY MARIO A PLUG WAS INSERTED. MARINE POLLUTION CONT. WAS CALLED TO PUMP OFF 2 COMP. MARIO ALSO NOTIFIED D. DICKEY AND PETER FISHER OF PUBLIC RELATIONS. J. BOYKO WAS NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED TO GO TOINWOOD TO HANDLE COMMUNICATIONS ETC. WHEN MARINE POLLUTION ARRIVED AT 02:30 THEY WERE INSTRUCTED TO PUMP OFF COMPARTMENTS #1 & 2. AFTER PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO ENSURE SAFETY AND REDUCE ANY FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS (L.I.E. SHUT DOWN BOTH DIRECTIONS, FOAM BLANKET SPREAD, WATER MIST APPLIED OVER VACUUM TRUCK EXHAUST) THE DOME COVERS WERE OPENED INDIVIDUALLY, PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED BEGINNING AT 03:00, THE PUMP OFF PROCEDURE LASTED 50 MIN. AND ENDED AT 03:50. TOTAL GALS REMOVED FROM COMPARTMENTS 1 & 2 WAS 4588 GALS. FROM COMPARTMENTS WHICH HAD PREVIOUSLY HELD A TOTAL OF 4700 GALS. MARINES TRUCK THEN PROCEEDED TO THE INWOOD PLANT TO PUMP OFF THE JRODUCT AT WHICH TIME WE METERED AND SAMPLED THE GASOLINE TO VERIFY MEASUREMENTS TAKEN AT THE SCENE. THE REMAINING TWO COMPARTMENTS WERE THEN TAKEN FROM THE SCENE AT 04:30 TO RFM INC. 3 EXITS FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AND DROPPED INTO THE CORRESPONDING TANKS. AT THIS TIME A D.O.T. OFFICER, MARIO AND FRANK WENNER OUR CONTRACT MECHANIC REMOVED THE #1 INTERNAL VALVE FOR INSPECTION. IT WAS VERIFIED BY ALL PARTIES THAT THE VALVE WAS IN GOOD WORKING ORDER. HOWEVER, THE D.O.T. OFFICER STILL ISSUED A SUMMONS ATTRIBUTING THE #1 COMPARTMENT LEAK TO A FAULTY INTERNAL VALVE, WE MAINTAIN THE LEAK IS ATTRIBUTABLE TO THE IMPACT.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF AQ80 ON FEBRUARY 5, 1990, THE RAMP CREW DISCOVERED SPILLED GASOLINE IN THE AFT PORTION OF THE FORWARD PIT. I WAS NOTIFIED AT 0640 BY THE LOADMAN OF THE GASOLINE SPIL. THE RAMP SERVICEMENT WIPED UP THE GASOLINE. THE MECHANIC CHECKED UNDER THE FLOOR PANELS FOR LIQUID FUEL. THERE WAS NONE. THE PLANE WAS DISPATCHED 85 MINUTES LATE WITHOUT PASSENGERS. ALL PASSENGERS WERE ACCOMMODATED ON EARLY FLIGHTS.  WOODEN PLYBOARD BOX EST. 12" WIDE X 15" HEIGHT X 18" LONG, WITH PADLOCK.  TAG - EXECUTIVE CLUB/KOA 39-7751.  CONTENTS - HONDA PORTABLE GENERATOR MODEL EX800.  I CHECKED THE GAS TANK AFTER THE PASSENGERS OPENED THE BOX, THE TANK WAS NEARLY FULL EXCEPT FOR AN ESTIMATED 8 TO 10 OUNCES WHICH HAS SPLASHED OUT OF THE OVERFLOW VENT DURING THE FLIGHT FROM HONOLULU TO KONA.

THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG TO CANTAIN THE SPILL. UPON INVESTIGATION, THE BOX WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 30 PLASTIC JARS OF APPROXIMATELY 2 0ZS EACH. 16 WERE PACKED IN AN ABX LAB PACK PACKAGE AND WERE NOT LEAKING . 14 WERE PACKED IN ZIP-LOC BAGS, 2 TO A BAG.  TWO OF THESE BAGS WERE LEAKING . APPROXIMATELY 50 ML WAS LOST. THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION WAS PROPERLY FILLED OUT AND ALL MARKINGS WERE CORRECT WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE ORIENTATION MARKINGS AND THE PRESENCE OF A PREPRINTED CLASS 4 LABEL ON THE BOX. THE ORIENTATION MARKINGS WERE ARROWS WITH THE WORD "UP" PRINTED NEXT TO THEM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE WILMINGTON HAZARDOUS SORT UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING PAA RELEASE.

column168: ON 2/1/90, L MEENEY, DRIVER FOR LINDEN MOTOR FREIGHT CO., INC, CALLED HIS LOCAL DISPATCHER AND ADVISED THEM THAT HE DETECTED A LEAKING DRUM OF METHYL METHACRYLATE MONOMER INHIBITED, HAZARDOUS CLASSIFICATION, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1247, IN THE NOSE OF HIS TRAILER, CAUSE UNKNOWN. HE WAS ON HILLSIDE AVENUE, RICHMOND HILL, NEW YORK, WHEN THE LEAK WAS DETECTED. THE DRIVER SECURED HIS VEHICLE AND PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE LEAK, TO INSURE THAT NO PRODUCT WAS ALLOWED TO GET ON THE GROUND. OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR, IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, THROUGH CHEMTREC OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS ADVISIED, BY THEM, TO NOTIFY THE NEW YORK CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, (718) 476-6200, OF THE INCIDENT, LOCATION AND THE ACTION TAKEN BY OUR DRIVER AND THE ETA OF THE CUSTOMER'S HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM. NEW YORK CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL SECURED THE SCENE, RESTRICTED ACCESS TO THE UNIT, WHILE AWAITING ARRIVAL OF THE TEAM ON THE SCENE. CLEAN-UP COMMENCED AT 1940 AND THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS OVERPACKED AND SECURED BY 2145.

column168: AT 0918 HOURS, A TRAIN PASSING TRACK 203 OBSERVED LIQUID COMING FROM TANK CAR IN QUESTION WHICH WAS REPORTED TO NORTH LITTLE ROCK CREST TOWER. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C. L. HILL RESPONDED. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET WHICH HAD BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OFF AND HANGING BY CHAIN. AGENT HILL ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS. CLEANED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND CHECKED GASKET, APPLIED OUTLET CAP TO BOTTOM OUTLET AND TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED LEAK. NOTIFIED CHEMTREC'S JOE DEBNAM OF INCIDENT WHO NOTIFIED SHIPPER. CALL WAS RECEIVED FROM SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RICHARD JONS WHO WAS INFORMED OF DEFECTIVE OUTLET VALVE, FURTHER THAT LEG OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WOULD CONTAIN PRODUCT AND THAT CAUTION SHOULD BE TAKEN WHILE UNLOADING. MR. JONS WAS ADVISED OF FOLLOWING VIOLATIONS NOTED IN AGENT HILL'S INSPECTION. AIR INLET VALVE HAD PLUG REMOVED. ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WAS LOOSE DUE TO BOLT THREADS STRIPPED. PLUG WAS SECURED TO AIR VALVE. THREE WASHERS WERE PLACED UNDER MANWAY COVER BOLT NUT WHICH SECURED MANWAY COVER. MR JONS ADVISED CONSIGNEE WOULD BE ALERTED TO DEFECTIVE VALVE AND CAUTION SHOULD BE TAKEN WHEN UNLOADING CAR, FURTHER THAT CAR WOULD BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS TO OUTLET VALVE FOLLOWING UNLOADING.

column168: TRAILER REAZ 659927, PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, WAS REPORTED WITH A LOAD SHIFT SEVERE ENOUGH TO CAUSE THE REAR TRAILER DOORS TO BULGE OPEN. IMMEDIATE RESPONSE AND INSPECTION BY SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT R.R. MORRISON DETERMINED THAT TRAILER HAD NO APPARENT OR VISIBLE LEAKAGE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1520 HOURS, SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ART GARDNER WAS ADVISED OF THE SHIFTED LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE. FURTHER INSPECTION OF TRAILER WAS MADE AND A STAINING OF THE FLOOR WAS SEEN. THE TRAILER WAS DERAMPED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. AN INSPECTION OF CONTENTS INSIDE TRAILER MADE TO DETERMINE IF LADING WAS DAMAGED OR LEAKING. DURING THE EARLY EVENING HOURS OF 2/13 THE SHIPPER (NORTHWEST ENVIRO SERVICE INC.) WAS CONTACTED FOR A MORE COMPLETE DESCRIPTION OF THE CONTENTS AND ITS HAZARDOUS CHARACTERISTICS. THEIR SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THE TRAILER ACTUALLY CONTAINED FIFTY-SIX 55 GALLON DRUMS OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID (HAZARDOUS WASTE/PAINT RELATED MATERIALS? AND SIX LARGE PLASTIC WRAPPED BALES OF SOLVENT CONTAMINATED RAGS. DURING THE LATE EVENING HOURS OF 2/13 SPECIAL AGENT GARDNER MADE AN INTERIOR INSPECTION OF TRAILER AND DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED. THE BALES ON PALLETS HAD NOT BEEN BANDED NOR BLOCKED OR BRACED. ALSO THE 56 DRUMS HAD BEEN LOADED WITHOUT ANY BLOCKING OR BRACING, WITH THE EXCEPTION OF 2 SHORT 2'X4' PIECES OF LUMBER AT THE REAR OF TRAILER, AND THE PLASTIC WRAPPED BALES OF RAGS HAD BEEN TORN OPEN.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT C.E. ZERWECK WAS CALLED TO THE ARLINGTON, TEXAS BOP YARD BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS DUANE HUNT REGARDING THE ABOVE CAR. A SWITCH CREW HAD REPORTED SEEING A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD AROUND THE MANWAY. THE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN THE TIE-UP TRACK. MR. ZERWECK DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BURST. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A LIKE DISC AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

TRAIN MANAGEMENT IN OMAHA, REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 61136, MOVING IN TRAIN Y RSC 16, APPEARED TO BE FUMING FROM A FITTING ON TOP OF THE CAR. CAR WAS BIL LED AS HYDROCHLORIC ACID, RESIDUE, AND WAS EASTBOUND OUT OF CALIENTE, NV. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE MOVE THE CAR INTO SALT LAKE. IT ARRIVED AT 1 845 HOURS. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC WAS MISSING AND THE CAP MISSING. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE. REPAIRS CONSISTED OF PLUGGI NG THE VENT WITH A WOOD PLUG. A DISC COULDN'T BE APPLIED AS THE VENT CAP AS SEMBLY WAS MISSING. REPAIRS COMPLETE AT 1930 HOURS. FINAL REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE CAR AT CLIMAX CHEMICAL.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: MR RUSS KELLYOF THE FRA FOND TANK CAR AMOX 23914 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOT TOM OUTLET VALVE. SPECIAL AGENT HAZ MAT H W RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED AND CAR WAS MOVED TO TRACK 103 FOR REPAIR. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OU TLET VALVE CAP WAS LOOSE. THE DEFECT WAS CORRECTED BY MAKING A HALF TURN ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WITH A 36-INCH PIPE WRENCH. CAR WAS REJECTED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT BACK TO AMOCO FOR ADDITIONAL R EPAIR AND CLEANING. THE SPILL AREA ON THE TANK CAR WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SOD IUM BICARBONATE AND WATER. REPAIR WAS COMPLETED AT 1030HRS.

CARMEN ADVISED THAT LIQUID SPLASHING FROM FITTINGS ON THE TOP AREA OF TANK CAR. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZ MAT DON LOW, RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMI NED THAT 2 SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON MANWAY. TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND WASHED OFF THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR AND RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MANAGER HAZ MAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS CONTACTED AT 5:15PM FEB 2, BY CHIEF DISPATCHER ADVISING  TAN CAR MWSX 29650 WAS INVOLVED IN A YARD DERAILMENT IN ATCHISON, KS, AND HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. ASSISTANCE FROM AAR BU REAU OF EXPLOSIVES CHIEF INSPECTOR A.D. MATY WAS REQUESTED. A CONFERENCE CALL WAS MADE TO THE ATCHISON FIRE DEPT DISPATCHER. HE ADVISED THE FIRE DEPT HAD BEEN ABLE TO SLOW THE LEAK AND THE IMMEDIATE CONCERN WAS OBTAINING EQUIPMENT TO PUMP THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CAR. STINE RETURNED TO KANSAS CITY AND OBTAINED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRANSFER UNIT. ON ARRIVAL, HE WAS MET BY FIRE CHIEF MICHAEL MCDERMID, WHO INDICATED THEY HAD PLACED A DAM ACROSS THE TRACKS JUST NORTH OF THE DERAILED CARS WHICH CONTAINED THE RUNOFF OF THE ALCOHOL AS WELL AS THE WATER WHICH WAS USED IN VAPOR REPRESSION. MIDWE ST GRAIN REPRESENTATIVE, JOHN WOHYGEMUTH, AND DWIGHT DUNSTER WERE IN THE PROCESS OF PUMPING ALCOHOL FROM THE DAMAGED TANK CAR MWSSX 29620 AND IT WAS LOADED AT 9:15PM. THE PRODUCT WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM THE DAMAGED CAR WAS VACU UMED UP AND PLACED IN TANK CAR NATX 24323 FOR DISPOSAL. ALL THE RECOVERED P RODUCT  WHICH WAS PUMPED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND THE TANK CAR WERE RETURNED TO MIDWEST. ARRANGEMENTS  WERE MADE WITH PAPILLON CREEK SEWAGE TREATMENT PLAN T MANAGER, OPPD, TO MIX THE RECOVERED LIQUID IN EQUAL AMOUNTS WITH THE NORM AL OIL SLUDGE FOR DISPOSAL BY INEMERSTION.

STINE, WAS CONTACTED BY UNION PACI FIC RAILROAD'S MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, WHO ADVISED SWITCH CREWS WERE COMP LAINING OF STRONG AMMONIA ODOR AT THE WEST END OF TRACK 204.
